330
00:17:14,848 --> 00:17:17,330
So in order to build this monster,

331
00:17:17,530 --> 00:17:19,311
we needed to be disciplined in how we built it,

332
00:17:19,411 --> 00:17:22,493
and we needed to be free to iterate and scale,

333
00:17:22,513 --> 00:17:25,035
scope as we work without costing the art at the same time.

334
00:17:26,616 --> 00:17:28,837
And this massive enterprise couldn't have been possible

335
00:17:28,897 --> 00:17:30,678
without the help of our world managers.

336
00:17:31,259 --> 00:17:33,800
They played a key role in organizing the production

337
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:36,702
and supporting the director's vision was the key here.

338
00:17:38,987 --> 00:17:41,709
So we did change the team structures to be more agile,

339
00:17:41,809 --> 00:17:44,391
so not fully agile, but our own version of agile.

340
00:17:45,011 --> 00:17:48,473
So each core art department had their own product owner,

341
00:17:48,934 --> 00:17:51,435
empowering the experts to be responsible for the quality

342
00:17:51,455 --> 00:17:53,957
and quantity of asset produced for the game world.

343
00:17:55,158 --> 00:17:56,999
So by trusting our people,

344
00:17:57,079 --> 00:17:59,941
we've created engagement and commitment amongst them,

345
00:18:00,341 --> 00:18:02,382
and we can say that they all had a huge impact

346
00:18:02,422 --> 00:18:03,643
on the final look of the game

347
00:18:03,723 --> 00:18:05,945
because they were part of the decision-making process.

348
00:18:09,029 --> 00:18:10,450
So the notion of one team became something

349
00:18:10,470 --> 00:18:12,391
that was incredibly important for us throughout production

350
00:18:12,431 --> 00:18:14,572
and the slogan was something that we built on as we went.

351
00:18:15,212 --> 00:18:17,173
Coming off the back of Assassin's Creed Syndicate,

352
00:18:17,353 --> 00:18:18,874
we wanted to build on the relationships

353
00:18:18,914 --> 00:18:20,314
that we'd created to build that game.

354
00:18:21,095 --> 00:18:24,396
And we wanted to work together as one team under one vision.

355
00:18:24,897 --> 00:18:28,698
So we actually utilized the skill sets of nine other teams, led from Ubisoft Quebec,

356
00:18:29,218 --> 00:18:32,379
to utilize the skill sets of multiple different studios around the world,

357
00:18:32,559 --> 00:18:35,500
all focusing together and channeling their energy on this one vision,

358
00:18:35,780 --> 00:18:40,502
making sure that we could build a world that was cohesive and playable as one whole thing.

359
00:18:42,222 --> 00:18:43,363
So next came the world phasers.

360
00:18:44,304 --> 00:18:46,786
Now this phaser system isn't something

361
00:18:46,806 --> 00:18:48,167
that's brand spanking new.

362
00:18:48,207 --> 00:18:49,528
It's not rocket science, but it's something

363
00:18:49,548 --> 00:18:51,189
that I've been working, the way I've been working

364
00:18:51,209 --> 00:18:53,631
for many years, working back on games like Need for Speed.

365
00:18:54,172 --> 00:18:56,273
And it's a way of making sure that we can clearly define

366
00:18:56,354 --> 00:18:59,556
at separated gates how the world's gonna be

367
00:18:59,796 --> 00:19:01,738
and how you're gonna be able to play inside of that world

368
00:19:01,878 --> 00:19:04,060
at any different given time during production.

369
00:19:04,996 --> 00:19:13,994
So we knew that the scope of what we were trying to do was huge, so we needed to make sure we worked in a disciplined way to make sure we could make informed decisions at each step of the production process.

370
00:19:15,554 --> 00:19:16,935
So phase one was all about learning.

371
00:19:17,135 --> 00:19:18,577
So we'd been doing all this research,

372
00:19:18,597 --> 00:19:20,219
we'd gone back to school, we'd been getting help

373
00:19:20,239 --> 00:19:21,821
from a historian who was now in-house,

374
00:19:22,201 --> 00:19:24,284
but it was now time for the team to get that empowerment.

375
00:19:24,304 --> 00:19:26,867
It was time for the level artists, level designers,

376
00:19:26,947 --> 00:19:28,869
texturers, narrative team, everyone to start

377
00:19:28,889 --> 00:19:30,190
to understand this information.

378
00:19:30,711 --> 00:19:31,852
So at this point in the project,

379
00:19:32,213 --> 00:19:34,696
the level artists and level designers are working together

380
00:19:34,876 --> 00:19:35,977
as one world-building team.

381
00:19:37,018 --> 00:19:42,459
learning each other's skill set, understanding how each other's disciplines are important to each other.

382
00:19:43,059 --> 00:19:46,660
And they start to work on the information that we've put together as a group,

383
00:19:46,840 --> 00:19:48,620
and they start to input into that information.

384
00:19:49,200 --> 00:19:53,001
So we created lots of documentation, and this one specifically was interesting

385
00:19:53,021 --> 00:19:57,242
because it was a visual map that we created that had a host of different elements of information

386
00:19:57,262 --> 00:20:00,542
that could be tapped into, looking into the actual historical data

387
00:20:00,582 --> 00:20:02,543
of each of the different regions of ancient Greece.

388
00:20:03,023 --> 00:20:04,904
tapping into the trade, the population,

389
00:20:04,984 --> 00:20:07,505
whether it was an oligarchy or a monarchy,

390
00:20:08,286 --> 00:20:09,646
how big their army was,

391
00:20:10,127 --> 00:20:12,348
especially what kind of things they were making or doing,

392
00:20:12,388 --> 00:20:14,489
because that tapped into then what we wanted to do

393
00:20:14,529 --> 00:20:16,190
with that region to give it its thematic.

394
00:20:18,051 --> 00:20:19,452
From that, the team then started to build

395
00:20:19,492 --> 00:20:21,573
their own world documents, which we could then look into,

396
00:20:21,933 --> 00:20:24,254
giving them the creativity to take all this information

397
00:20:24,295 --> 00:20:27,116
we've been giving them and start to build up the plans

398
00:20:27,196 --> 00:20:28,577
for what they want to do with the world

399
00:20:28,857 --> 00:20:29,958
and how the world's going to be built

400
00:20:30,098 --> 00:20:31,238
based around this information.

401
00:20:32,665 --> 00:20:35,726
As part of the phase one, we built what we call the paper maps.

402
00:20:35,766 --> 00:20:39,447
So we created 2D Photoshop maps of every single region of the world.

403
00:20:40,047 --> 00:20:42,848
And we looked into how the topology was going to work.

404
00:20:42,868 --> 00:20:46,308
What we were going to see in terms of, is it going to be foresty?

405
00:20:46,368 --> 00:20:47,889
Is it going to be fields?

406
00:20:48,349 --> 00:20:50,550
And what kind of cultivation is going to be happening?

407
00:20:51,010 --> 00:20:54,110
And we did this for the entire Greek world before we did anything in 3D,

408
00:20:54,491 --> 00:20:57,931
allowing us to communicate clearly with each of the different departments

409
00:20:58,311 --> 00:20:59,072
what they were going to get.

410
00:20:59,312 --> 00:21:01,732
Obviously, this is not final, things are going to change.

411
00:21:02,172 --> 00:21:04,973
But it allowed the quest team to start looking at where their quest hubs are going to be.

412
00:21:05,273 --> 00:21:08,334
The narrative team could tap into the different thematics we were planning on doing,

413
00:21:08,354 --> 00:21:09,874
so they could write stories around that

414
00:21:10,214 --> 00:21:13,255
and start to decide where key characters are going to be positioned throughout the world.

415
00:21:15,251 --> 00:21:18,254
So there comes thematization or pizza slice

416
00:21:18,334 --> 00:21:20,275
as we love to call this.

417
00:21:20,816 --> 00:21:24,319
So building such a massive world made out of tons of cities,

418
00:21:24,399 --> 00:21:29,523
villages, sanctuaries, and everything you can think of.

419
00:21:29,844 --> 00:21:32,046
For us, thematization was super important

420
00:21:32,166 --> 00:21:35,168
because we didn't want our player to have a sentiment

421
00:21:35,228 --> 00:21:36,930
or deja vu as we say in French.

422
00:21:37,390 --> 00:21:40,553
So we work a lot with thematization and simplification.

423
00:21:40,613 --> 00:21:42,435
So let's say, for example, within a city.

424
00:21:43,117 --> 00:21:46,458
like Athens, which would be made out of several districts.

425
00:21:47,218 --> 00:21:48,959
Each district had their own thematic,

426
00:21:49,039 --> 00:21:51,400
so let's say the pottery zone will have only potteries

427
00:21:51,440 --> 00:21:52,781
and maybe oven to cook potteries,

428
00:21:52,821 --> 00:21:55,122
but we would avoid placing too much prop in it

429
00:21:55,162 --> 00:21:56,823
so the player could easily identify

430
00:21:57,283 --> 00:21:59,404
what that region was about.

431
00:21:59,444 --> 00:22:02,185
And we did that same recipe throughout the old world

432
00:22:02,205 --> 00:22:04,126
to make sure that the player will never encounter

433
00:22:04,146 --> 00:22:05,707
the same recipe all over the place.

434
00:22:08,992 --> 00:22:12,094
With the documentation and paper maps in place and approved,

435
00:22:12,154 --> 00:22:14,636
we started to look at how the terrain was going to work.

436
00:22:14,916 --> 00:22:16,597
The terrain forms the foundation of everything

437
00:22:16,617 --> 00:22:17,138
we're going to do.

438
00:22:17,478 --> 00:22:19,700
And it was incredibly important to the ancient Greeks.

439
00:22:19,760 --> 00:22:21,421
They used the terrain very logically

440
00:22:21,461 --> 00:22:23,503
to use it for fortification and use it

441
00:22:23,543 --> 00:22:25,724
for where they're going to plan to place their cities.

442
00:22:26,165 --> 00:22:29,267
So we referenced elements such as digital elevation data

443
00:22:29,287 --> 00:22:31,008
from NASA, a lot of Google Earth.

444
00:22:31,048 --> 00:22:33,130
I think a lot of people were zooming in on Greece

445
00:22:33,170 --> 00:22:34,291
quite often during this project.

446
00:22:34,771 --> 00:22:36,452
And then as well as that, the reference that we took

447
00:22:36,492 --> 00:22:38,754
when we went out to Greece to build up a visual picture

448
00:22:39,094 --> 00:22:41,296
of the simplification of the terrain at this point,

449
00:22:41,676 --> 00:22:43,658
so that we could create these honeycomb elements

450
00:22:43,738 --> 00:22:45,059
around the different regions of the game.

451
00:22:45,819 --> 00:22:47,060
And jumping forward a little bit,

452
00:22:47,100 --> 00:22:48,922
what we did with that terrain then was hand it off

453
00:22:48,962 --> 00:22:50,243
to our three terrain artists

454
00:22:50,323 --> 00:22:53,505
who covered the entire 256 square kilometers of Greece,

455
00:22:54,466 --> 00:22:56,988
working that basic terrain through Mudbox,

456
00:22:57,068 --> 00:22:58,849
sculpting it into something that's more defined,

457
00:22:59,169 --> 00:23:01,271
and then adding the erosion paths through World Machine

458
00:23:01,331 --> 00:23:02,852
to give us the final version of the terrain

459
00:23:02,872 --> 00:23:04,073
that we see in the game today.

460
00:23:06,423 --> 00:23:09,045
So now that our terrain was giving shape,

461
00:23:09,465 --> 00:23:11,907
we could start kicking in the biome team and the loop.

462
00:23:12,367 --> 00:23:14,288
So under the leadership of Rensana Muteng,

463
00:23:14,308 --> 00:23:15,889
which was the biome leader,

464
00:23:16,949 --> 00:23:17,810
we established that

465
00:23:20,175 --> 00:23:23,337
The world needed great visual diversity,

466
00:23:23,657 --> 00:23:25,699
so the biome played a key role into that.

467
00:23:25,759 --> 00:23:28,921
So we had to make sure that each of our biome

468
00:23:28,941 --> 00:23:30,342
were contrasted from one another.

469
00:23:30,482 --> 00:23:32,664
And in fact, there's probably two biome in Greece,

470
00:23:32,744 --> 00:23:35,126
but we decided to play with season and exotic biome

471
00:23:35,146 --> 00:23:37,107
to make sure that the land look and feel different

472
00:23:37,167 --> 00:23:37,787
as an overall.

473
00:23:38,828 --> 00:23:40,909
So here we did apply the same technique

474
00:23:40,969 --> 00:23:42,130
as we did for everything else.

475
00:23:42,370 --> 00:23:43,851
Based on our study and research,

476
00:23:44,251 --> 00:23:46,893
we started to create like elevation stripes.

477
00:23:47,053 --> 00:23:49,995
So based, we took so many picture

478
00:23:50,075 --> 00:23:51,916
and we found also picture all over the place.

479
00:23:52,296 --> 00:23:54,177
We established like which type of plant

480
00:23:54,217 --> 00:23:57,479
were growing at different type of elevation

481
00:23:58,580 --> 00:23:59,520
in the Greek landscape,

482
00:23:59,580 --> 00:24:01,402
because that's how our biome recipe

483
00:24:01,422 --> 00:24:03,123
were applied by per elevation.

484
00:24:03,723 --> 00:24:06,845
So we did that same technique for every biome.

485
00:24:06,885 --> 00:24:07,585
And once we were.

486
00:24:08,540 --> 00:24:12,363
happy with the result and making sure that each biome look and feel different from one another,

487
00:24:12,443 --> 00:24:17,947
we could start the production of them. So when we do a biome, we need to produce every asset

488
00:24:18,067 --> 00:24:25,132
that takes place in it. So we need to produce all the trees, bushes, clutter, name it. There's a lot

489
00:24:25,152 --> 00:24:32,317
of them. And also we needed to produce all the textures for all those vegetation assets. And

490
00:24:32,337 --> 00:24:34,918
the same thing applies to the rocks, boulders, ground textures.

491
00:24:36,189 --> 00:24:38,350
For this production, and we'll talk it very soon,

492
00:24:38,390 --> 00:24:40,210
we use substance designers, substance painters

493
00:24:40,230 --> 00:24:42,571
to produce all our material and texture.

494
00:24:45,872 --> 00:24:47,713
Water, Ben briefly talked about water,

495
00:24:47,773 --> 00:24:49,273
but the water play a massive role

496
00:24:49,293 --> 00:24:50,574
in our role in gameplay experience.

497
00:24:51,074 --> 00:24:54,235
Since 60 percent of our world's surface is made out of water,

498
00:24:54,355 --> 00:24:56,236
we try to create the most awesome

499
00:24:56,276 --> 00:24:59,337
and diversified experience when it comes to water,

500
00:24:59,397 --> 00:25:00,717
and we treat it as a main character.

501
00:25:01,768 --> 00:25:05,618
So we wanted to be able to convey a feeling of embarking on a true odyssey,

502
00:25:05,658 --> 00:25:08,967
which means being able to travel by boat and engage in naval combat.

503
00:25:09,742 --> 00:25:12,383
So the agency is the host of many dangers and treasures

504
00:25:12,443 --> 00:25:13,924
which will tempt the player to set sail,

505
00:25:14,164 --> 00:25:16,506
explore its farthest reach and dive into its depth.

506
00:25:17,126 --> 00:25:19,148
And so we are pretty happy to have created

507
00:25:19,228 --> 00:25:20,669
a seamless naval experience.

508
00:25:22,009 --> 00:25:27,293
So here you'll see the first volumetric foam

509
00:25:27,393 --> 00:25:31,095
and crashing wave test that we did with our friends

510
00:25:31,115 --> 00:25:34,437
in Bucharest which were in charge of our water.

511
00:25:34,477 --> 00:25:37,419
So flowing wave and volumetric foam were super important

512
00:25:37,459 --> 00:25:38,240
in the big challenge.

513
00:25:39,021 --> 00:25:41,144
As you can see, it's even lagging because it's a prototype.

514
00:25:41,385 --> 00:25:46,272
But once we saw that, we knew that we had something very special in our end,

515
00:25:46,352 --> 00:25:49,658
and we are more than happy with the in-game result that we have right now.

516
00:25:52,406 --> 00:25:55,669
But even with seven key biomes, we thought it was not enough.

517
00:25:56,150 --> 00:25:59,173
Our landscape is so huge that we needed more.

518
00:25:59,233 --> 00:26:01,835
So we've created sub-biomes to make sure

519
00:26:01,855 --> 00:26:04,879
to offer the most visual diversity to our players.

520
00:26:04,979 --> 00:26:09,203
So we've created here the clay mine, the snow peak,

521
00:26:09,263 --> 00:26:12,226
cap mountains, marshland, and also burnt forest as example.

522
00:26:16,098 --> 00:26:18,279
So running in parallel with the biome work,

523
00:26:18,299 --> 00:26:20,240
the world building team are starting to put together

524
00:26:20,260 --> 00:26:22,120
what we called phase three, which is gray blocking.

525
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:23,841
Again, not a new notion whatsoever.

526
00:26:24,241 --> 00:26:27,082
The one thing that was incredibly important to us

527
00:26:27,482 --> 00:26:29,462
was to make sure that we did this gray blocking pass

528
00:26:29,482 --> 00:26:31,303
for the entirety of the Greek landscape

529
00:26:31,363 --> 00:26:32,863
so that we could make informed decisions

530
00:26:32,943 --> 00:26:34,584
on how things were laying in the land,

531
00:26:34,664 --> 00:26:36,984
the relationship between the urban sanctuaries

532
00:26:37,024 --> 00:26:38,145
and villages and cities

533
00:26:38,565 --> 00:26:40,285
and the natural terrain and landscape

534
00:26:40,645 --> 00:26:43,806
so that we could move forward with a logical step

535
00:26:43,846 --> 00:26:44,746
at each phase of the way.

536
00:26:45,167 --> 00:26:48,009
but also so that the entire game could be played very, very early on.

537
00:26:48,049 --> 00:26:51,412
You could explore the entire world and we could have the Quest team play it

538
00:26:51,452 --> 00:26:53,234
and they could start planning where things are going to be,

539
00:26:53,654 --> 00:26:56,157
sight lines between quest givers and quest objectives.

540
00:26:56,457 --> 00:26:58,859
So it was very important for us to get this in very, very quickly.

541
00:26:59,279 --> 00:27:02,863
The top two screens there are actually from Athens that we built in 2016

542
00:27:03,303 --> 00:27:05,565
and the layout of Athens hasn't really changed that much.

543
00:27:05,585 --> 00:27:07,367
It's just that we've evolved on it over time.

544
00:27:08,356 --> 00:27:11,819
One of the other big things that Thierry tapped on as one of our six key points was the notion of

545
00:27:13,340 --> 00:27:17,264
two weekly sprints. So every two weeks we would get together with the entire team

546
00:27:17,584 --> 00:27:21,528
and showcase the work of the world team. And this was the entire world, we'd make a video

547
00:27:21,748 --> 00:27:26,472
over the weekend before the week before, the presentation would be on the Monday,

548
00:27:26,852 --> 00:27:32,397
and we could showcase to everybody the world that was going to be available to play that week in the build.

549
00:27:32,777 --> 00:27:34,740
and it allowed us to have constant communication,

550
00:27:34,820 --> 00:27:36,101
constant feedback from the team,

551
00:27:36,542 --> 00:27:39,205
and be able to see the progression of the world

552
00:27:39,385 --> 00:27:40,126
as we move forward.

553
00:27:41,228 --> 00:27:43,550
To do that, we're gonna need architecture, and lots of it.

554
00:27:44,291 --> 00:27:46,534
So this was the product owner for architecture,

555
00:27:46,574 --> 00:27:47,796
who is Dominique Ladut-Party.

556
00:27:48,336 --> 00:27:51,197
who had a lot of experience working on previous Assassin's Creed titles,

557
00:27:51,237 --> 00:27:55,499
so he was a great person to take on the architecture mandate for us during Odyssey.

558
00:27:55,879 --> 00:27:59,220
And again, he started the process, and you'll hear us repeat this a couple of times more,

559
00:27:59,880 --> 00:28:03,402
making sure he tapped into the historical information that was available for architecture,

560
00:28:03,422 --> 00:28:08,964
because while the notion of Greek architecture is something I think most people can picture,

561
00:28:09,344 --> 00:28:13,825
the number of details and fine elements that actually go into making these buildings is incredible,

562
00:28:14,166 --> 00:28:16,707
and it was important for us to make sure that we built them in a correct manner.

563
00:28:17,915 --> 00:28:19,756
So throughout our research, we've learned something

564
00:28:19,796 --> 00:28:20,917
that we did not expect.

565
00:28:21,617 --> 00:28:23,338
Archaeologists have found that everything

566
00:28:23,378 --> 00:28:24,719
was painted back then.

567
00:28:24,799 --> 00:28:26,760
So from an art direction point of view,

568
00:28:26,820 --> 00:28:28,121
that kind of was a blessing.

569
00:28:28,221 --> 00:28:31,323
So we took that opportunity and add colors

570
00:28:31,383 --> 00:28:32,864
almost all man-made structures,

571
00:28:33,504 --> 00:28:37,247
which gave us a very unique, incredible way

572
00:28:37,327 --> 00:28:40,509
of how ancient Greece could have looked like

573
00:28:40,549 --> 00:28:42,830
2,500 years ago, which I think is fairly incredible.

574
00:28:43,950 --> 00:28:46,711
So historically, colors have always been seen

575
00:28:46,811 --> 00:28:48,912
as a status symbol, and our collective tastes

576
00:28:48,932 --> 00:28:50,472
have definitely changed over centuries.

577
00:28:50,532 --> 00:28:53,293
So seeing those statues, classic statues,

578
00:28:53,593 --> 00:28:55,294
recreated in vivid colors seems gaudy,

579
00:28:55,354 --> 00:28:56,494
almost obscene to us today,

580
00:28:56,514 --> 00:28:58,855
because we expect ancient Greek statuary

581
00:28:58,875 --> 00:29:01,176
to bear that dignified blank white look.

582
00:29:01,916 --> 00:29:03,257
But then when they were created,

583
00:29:03,317 --> 00:29:05,477
bright colors helped them to give detail

584
00:29:05,497 --> 00:29:06,678
and depth to the sculptures,

585
00:29:06,878 --> 00:29:08,598
and even according to the artists

586
00:29:08,759 --> 00:29:10,159
and art lover of that time period.

587
00:29:10,661 --> 00:29:13,425
their statues were considered ugly and unsightly.

588
00:29:13,946 --> 00:29:16,008
So that's why you're seeing a lot of painted statues

589
00:29:16,048 --> 00:29:18,272
in Assassin's Creed Odyssey, because we wanted to stay true

590
00:29:18,312 --> 00:29:19,954
to how they were back then.

591
00:29:21,734 --> 00:29:24,917
But just because we're making a game based in history doesn't mean we're making a recreation.

592
00:29:24,957 --> 00:29:28,321
There's still an awful lot of creativity that goes into building this world.

593
00:29:28,721 --> 00:29:31,424
And we relied heavily on our concept artists, especially early on,

594
00:29:31,484 --> 00:29:35,828
because like we said, a lot of the things that we were going to try and build in our game don't exist anymore.

595
00:29:35,868 --> 00:29:38,931
They're merely just bricks in the ground, or in most cases,

596
00:29:38,951 --> 00:29:42,154
they've been rebuilt on top of from many other civilizations.

597
00:29:42,735 --> 00:29:44,316
So with all this information about color,

598
00:29:44,616 --> 00:29:48,620
we started to tap into the concept of how we were going to compose the different elements of the game,

599
00:29:48,740 --> 00:29:54,244
especially for some of the things like the suburbs and places that aren't concentrated on so much by archaeologists.

600
00:29:54,825 --> 00:29:57,467
And they were able to start producing these strips that we created

601
00:29:57,527 --> 00:29:59,408
that would then be used by the world building team

602
00:29:59,469 --> 00:30:02,151
to build the composition of cities and villages throughout the world.

603
00:30:02,491 --> 00:30:04,212
But also looking at the materials and the colors,

604
00:30:04,593 --> 00:30:06,654
a lot of elements in Greece were actually built out of wood,

605
00:30:06,694 --> 00:30:08,256
which was something that we never expected.

606
00:30:08,756 --> 00:30:12,083
So wooden temples was something that was a bit of a surprise to us and allowed us to bring a

607
00:30:12,163 --> 00:30:15,189
flavor and a thematic to Greece that I think most people didn't expect to see.

608
00:30:16,517 --> 00:30:17,738
As well as that, we wanted to be,

609
00:30:18,858 --> 00:30:20,940
it was important to us to make sure we tapped into

610
00:30:21,260 --> 00:30:23,562
the history beyond the history that we were recreating.

611
00:30:24,022 --> 00:30:25,703
So the ancient Greeks of our time period

612
00:30:25,743 --> 00:30:28,925
were aware of the Mycenaean and the Minoan civilizations

613
00:30:28,965 --> 00:30:31,027
that had come before, so it was important for us

614
00:30:31,067 --> 00:30:33,289
to make sure we captured that, and the team went ahead

615
00:30:33,329 --> 00:30:35,330
and made the Mycenaean and Minoan kits for us

616
00:30:35,350 --> 00:30:37,351
to be able to utilize on the world-building side

617
00:30:37,391 --> 00:30:39,133
to create some of the really interesting POIs

618
00:30:39,153 --> 00:30:41,755
that you can explore, play, and in most cases, fight in.

619
00:30:43,308 --> 00:30:46,631
Here's a few examples of some of the other architecture kits that were built for the project.

620
00:30:47,152 --> 00:30:53,058
In total we built over 35 architecture kits and while you see them on this big one page there's a lot of similarities between them.

621
00:30:53,458 --> 00:31:05,170
As we mentioned before it's all about the fine details making sure that the columns are the correct type of column making sure that the pediments the correct type of pediment and these details were something that we really wanted to pay attention to to make a credible world.

622
00:31:07,505 --> 00:31:11,470
I think you will all agree that a world without texture would be missing something.

623
00:31:11,890 --> 00:31:15,694
So of course we have texture in Assassin's Creed Odyssey, but we did change something

624
00:31:15,734 --> 00:31:16,475
in our pipeline.

625
00:31:17,196 --> 00:31:21,160
And that wouldn't have been possible without the help of those two guys who did the talk

626
00:31:21,260 --> 00:31:24,584
on Tuesday and it's available, it's called Texturing the World of Assassin's Creed.

627
00:31:25,204 --> 00:31:29,349
So Vincent Desrosiers and Pierre Flo did make this change happen.

628
00:31:29,389 --> 00:31:30,050
So what?

629
00:31:31,050 --> 00:31:33,192
Prior to Assassin's Creed, I'd say most of the time,

630
00:31:33,212 --> 00:31:34,513
textures were created in Photoshop

631
00:31:34,553 --> 00:31:38,197
and exported in our in-house engine, which is Anvil.

632
00:31:38,757 --> 00:31:40,919
It's a proven technique. It's working very well.

633
00:31:41,379 --> 00:31:44,022
It can give awesome results,

634
00:31:44,082 --> 00:31:48,165
but we wanted something more homogeneous.

635
00:31:49,606 --> 00:31:53,109
And also that would react well under every lighting condition,

636
00:31:53,149 --> 00:31:55,311
so we wanted all our materials to be PBR,

637
00:31:55,351 --> 00:31:56,973
which means physically based rendering.

638
00:31:57,466 --> 00:32:00,908
So we integrated substance designer, substance painter

639
00:32:00,948 --> 00:32:02,248
throughout our pipeline.

640
00:32:02,729 --> 00:32:07,811
So meaning that every texture were, material were built using

641
00:32:07,831 --> 00:32:08,632
those two software.

642
00:32:09,192 --> 00:32:12,273
And also what they did is they used both software strings.

643
00:32:12,293 --> 00:32:16,215
So they used painter and substance main key points to

644
00:32:16,275 --> 00:32:17,316
create our materials.

645
00:32:17,956 --> 00:32:19,657
So the thing is the whole thing.

646
00:32:20,057 --> 00:32:23,299
converted and started to use those software as an overall.

647
00:32:23,339 --> 00:32:25,821
So every texture that you're seeing in Assassin's Creed Odyssey

648
00:32:26,201 --> 00:32:28,022
have been created using those two software.

649
00:32:28,923 --> 00:32:32,204
They've created a total of 1,500 textures

650
00:32:32,244 --> 00:32:35,867
with a relatively small team, which is very good.

651
00:32:35,907 --> 00:32:36,287
And the other...

652
00:32:36,947 --> 00:32:40,692
big aspect of working with substance designers is that we can iterate and very

653
00:32:40,732 --> 00:32:45,357
fast. It's a procedural software so we could ask for changes and they could

654
00:32:45,598 --> 00:32:49,602
react very fast and we could then polish our game which was a bit more difficult

655
00:32:49,903 --> 00:32:50,864
using the old technique.

656
00:32:53,330 --> 00:32:54,370
So the next part of the project,

657
00:32:54,410 --> 00:32:55,951
we're around about halfway through at this point,

658
00:32:55,991 --> 00:32:57,051
about one and a half years in,

659
00:32:57,211 --> 00:32:59,171
was what we called phase four, which was intent.

660
00:32:59,792 --> 00:33:00,812
So at this point of the project,

661
00:33:00,952 --> 00:33:02,272
especially on the world building side,

662
00:33:02,312 --> 00:33:04,073
was the first time we actually split the team

663
00:33:04,093 --> 00:33:06,414
between level art and level design specific disciplines

664
00:33:06,474 --> 00:33:08,014
so that we could start to focus in

665
00:33:08,394 --> 00:33:10,755
on the very key details of each of the two disciplines.

666
00:33:11,155 --> 00:33:12,436
The level designers making sure

667
00:33:12,476 --> 00:33:14,896
that they could make the most fun areas that they could,

668
00:33:15,196 --> 00:33:16,917
concentrating on the forts, the caves,

669
00:33:17,317 --> 00:33:19,558
making sure that the tombs were fun to explore

670
00:33:19,618 --> 00:33:21,818
and navigate and had a little bit of challenge and puzzle.

671
00:33:22,259 --> 00:33:25,802
while at the same time the level artists were making sure that the placement of every single

672
00:33:26,102 --> 00:33:30,746
object in the world was just perfect. So this came down to the two product owners for each

673
00:33:30,766 --> 00:33:35,350
of the disciplines. Mathieu Lechance was lead level designer and Safi Sader was in charge

674
00:33:35,450 --> 00:33:39,954
of the level art and these guys were the guys responsible for pushing the world to what we call

675
00:33:40,075 --> 00:33:40,315
alpha.

676
00:33:41,196 --> 00:33:50,008
So Alpha for us was one year before launch, an incredibly important milestone for us to ensure that we've got enough time to be able to polish the world to its full max that we can,

677
00:33:50,388 --> 00:33:55,135
making sure that we can change the world and tweak the world to make sure that the quests have got everything that they need,

678
00:33:55,455 --> 00:33:58,840
and we can tell the stories that we want the player to experience as they travel around the world.

